---
import StudyDataTable from "./studydatatable.astro";
---

<details
  id="safety"
  class="mt-1 w-full group border-b border-gray-200 pb-4 scroll-mt-20"
>
  <summary
    class="flex items-center cursor-pointer text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 hover:text-blue-600 list-none py-2"
  >
    <svg
      class="w-5 h-5 mr-2 transition-transform duration-300 ease-in-out group-open:rotate-180 flex-shrink-0"
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
      fill="none"
      viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      stroke="currentColor"
      stroke-width="2"
    >
      <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"
      ></path>
    </svg>
    <span>Safety: Proven 3 Times Safer Than N95 Mask</span>
  </summary>
  <div class="mt-2 w-full pl-5 animate-fade-in">
    <p class="mb-4 text-gray-700">
      MyAirHat™ offers significant safety advantages:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-2 mb-4 text-gray-700">
      <li>
        <strong>Integral face shield protects eyes:</strong> Provides built-in eye
        protection against droplets and aerosols that happen when others cough and
        sneeze.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No leaks due to poor fit:</strong> Unlike masks that rely on a tight
        seal against the face (which is often imperfect), MyAirHat™ creates a separated
        air environment.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <StudyDataTable />
    <div class="mt-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">
        Carbon Dioxide Effects on Submarine-Qualified Sailors
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        Ryder et al., Aerospace Medicine and Human Performance (2018)
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
        A 2018 study showed no significant differences in decision making
        between sailors exposed to 600, 2500, or 15,000 ppm CO₂ for 80 minutes. <a
          href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29789085/"
          class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
          target="_blank">Read the study</a
        >
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-gray-700">
        Today the U.S. Navy's recommended carbon dioxide exposure limits for
        submarines are 25,000 ppm (2.5%) for periods up to 24 hours, and 8,000
        ppm (0.8%) for durations up to 90 days. (See Table 3-3 at <a
          href="https://nap.nationalacademies.org/read/11170/chapter/5#59"
          class="text-blue-600 hover:underline"
          target="_blank">nap.nationalacademies.org/read/11170/chapter/5#59</a
        >.)
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</details>

<style>
  details > summary {
    list-style: none; /* Hide the default marker */
  }
  details > summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none; /* Hide the default marker in Webkit */
  }
  @keyframes fade-in {
    from {
      opacity: 0;
      transform: translateY(-10px);
    }
    to {
      opacity: 1;
      transform: translateY(0);
    }
  }
  details[open] > div {
    animation: fade-in 0.3s ease-out;
  }
</style>
